def line_of_best_fit(x, y, dataframe):

    # Fit a polynomial to the data

    data = pd.DataFrame({'x': x, 'y': y}).dropna()
    # Returns the coefficients for y = mx + b
    coefficients = np.polyfit(data['x'], data['y'], 1)

    # plugs these coefficients into the equation y = mx + b
    polynomial = np.poly1d(coefficients)

    # then I use this equation to do a linear transformation on the array of x
    # this new series of data are the points on my line of best fit
    dataframe['Line Of Best Fit'] = polynomial(x)

    return polynomial # this will return the slope and intersect which became important later.

# I used chatgpt to figure out which function in numpy to use,
# I found polyfit and poly1d would work
# then looked up the function on the numpy library to double check
# https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.poly1d.html
# https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.polyfit.html

# kinda bad function, only written for this code

def compare_change(year, global_polynomial, port_polynomial, city=city_name, same_axis=False):
    # make a dataframe 
    change = pd.DataFrame({
        'Year': year,
        'Global Change': global_polynomial[1]*year - global_polynomial[1]*year[0],
        f'{city} Change': port_polynomial[1]*year - port_polynomial[1]*year[0]})

    change.plot('Year', legend=True, ylabel="Accumulated Change in Celcius", color=['blue', 'red'])

    return change

# make function to speed up what I did in first section

def ma_lobf(x, y, data, name):
    data[f'{name} Temp Moving Average'] = y.dropna().rolling(5).mean()
    poly = line_of_best_fit(x, y, data)
    data.rename(columns={'Line Of Best Fit': f'{name} Line of Best Fit'}, inplace=True)
    return poly

# show the difference in rate of change of termperature between the pre-date and post-date

def ma_lobf(x, y, data, name):
    data[f'{name} Temp Moving Average'] = y.dropna().rolling(5).mean()
    poly = line_of_best_fit(x, y, data)
    data.rename(columns={'Line Of Best Fit': f'{name} Line of Best Fit'}, inplace=True)
    return poly

def compare_years(preyear, postyear, pre_poly, post_poly, name=city_name, date=date):
    # make a dataframe 
    change = pd.DataFrame({
        f'Pre-{date}': preyear,
        f'Post-{date}': postyear,
        f'Pre {name} {date} Line of Best Fit': pre_poly[1]*preyear - pre_poly[1]*preyear[0],
        f'Post {name} {date} Line of Best Fit': post_poly[1]*postyear - post_poly[1]*postyear[0]})

    change.plot(f'Pre-{date}', f'Pre {name} {date} Line of Best Fit', ylabel="Accumulated Change in Celcius") 
    change.plot(f'Post-{date}', f'Post {name} {date} Line of Best Fit', ax=plt.gca())
    plt.xlabel("Years")

    return change
